<br>
1.  First, you have to find the pictures you just took.  They're located in your EQ directory on your computer--normally in C:\Program Files\Everquest\ and they're named as EQ000001.BMP or EQ000014.BMP depending on how many you took.  If you deleted one along the way, EQ will fill that number with a new one the next time you take a screenshot.<br>
<hr><br>
2.  OK, now that you've found your stash, you need to compress those pictures.  They're HUGE and nobody wants to spend 4 or 5 minutes downloading a 1MB image that doesn't even fill the screen.  You'll need an image composer or converter program that converts to JPEG or JPG format.  Many people seem to be happy with <a href="http://download.cnet.com/downloads/0-10077-100-1808446.html?tag=st.dl.10012.list.10077-100-1808446">ACDSee Classic</a> or something like that.  I use Adobe PhotoDeluxe and Microsoft Image Composer, but PhotoDeluxe came free with both my scanner and my digital camera, and Image Composer came with FrontPage98.<br>
<hr><br>
3.  Got an image editor that can compress images?  Good.  Convert them to JPEG format.  You usually do this by opening the BMP (Bitmap) image file, then go to the Save As command in the File menu.  You'll wanna try a few different quality settings (if the program has them) for JPG images to get a feel for how much image quality you want to trade off for how little bandwidth.  Bigger file sizes often mean better detail, but not always.<br>
<hr><br>
4.  So what do you do with all these compressed pictures?  I'm glad you asked.  (No, really!)  Unless you have some semi-permanent connection to the internet, you probably shouldn't try running your own web server, so talk some other sucker into hosting your files on theirs.  Most ISP accounts come with about 5 MB free web space where you can store pictures, home pages, etc.  If yours came with web space, find out where you're supposed to upload these pictures to, and what the web address will be once you do so.  They should also be able to tell you how to upload stuff.  If you have questions about this, let me know and I'll try to write a how-to for that, too.<br>
<br>
Alternatively, you can get a <a href="http://www.geocities.com">Geocities</a> account, which has a niftly little upload tool that lets you do it all from a web page.  Or... You can email them to <a href="mailto:webmaster@thesentinent.com">webmaster@thesentinent.com</a> and I'll put them on the guild's web server  :D.  I'll be more than happy to host images and files for you guys.  Just /yell.<br>
<hr><br>
5.  At this point, we'll assume you have your pictures available on a web server somewhere.  All you need to know is the address for the pictures.  Just take the address for the picture and add a few little codes to it to make it appear on the forum like so:<br>
<br>
HTML version--  &ltimg src="http://www.thesentinent.com/images/guild2.gif"><br>
<br>
EzCodes version-- [image]http://www.thesentinent.com/images/guild2.gif[/image]<br>
<br>
To use the HTML version, you have to check the HTML box at the bottom.  This will disable all of your smileys and stuff for that EZBoard post.  The EzCodes version is much easier to type and lets you keep doing smileys--just make sure the HTML code box isn't checked and the EzCodes box is.  As a note, EZBoard signature are written in HTML, so you'll need to use the HTML code there instead of EzCodes.<br>
<br>
<hr><br>
<br>
